Kyle Hostetter's Used Cars Price Prediction¶

Problem Definition¶

The Context:¶

  • In recent years there has been higher demand for used cars in the Indian Market. The uncertainty of used car prices is higher than new cars. The reasons for this stem from having inflation rates, damage, mileage, and other factors that simply do not apply to new vehicles. By solving this issue there can be better prediction as to what the true value of a used car is with lower uncertainty.

The objective:¶

  • The intended goal is to build a machine learning model that best predicts the used car value for normal cars. While completing this task, there will be creation of visualizations and the need to explore the dataset for trends or special characteristics that could further impact our model’s performance. Insights will be generated during this EDA and analysis process that will give more input features or better representation for the model. After the analysis of the dataset, it is inferred that this model should be built to predict the car price for normal cars. Normal cars would be anything that is the most popular or has a price value within 3 times the deviation plus the mean of the car’s price. This was inferred after noticing that there were outliers in the dataset. It was later found that the outliers happened to be exotic/expensive cars.

The key questions:¶

  • Most of the key questions that needed to be answered were completed in the EDA and analysis portion of this process. But some questions that we can answer now would be:

What feature has the highest correlation with Price?

  • Power had the highest correlation with a value > .88 for Price and log Price. This was discovered during the bivariate heatmap analysis.

What features need to have log transformation to be done?

  • Only three features need log transformations. These were ‘Kilometers_Drive’, ‘Price’, and ‘New_Price’. This was done because of the large skewness to the right. Also, these columns had values that had very large ranges.

What feature engineering must be done to give the model more insight?

  • There was only column that was created through feature engineering. This was the ‘Manufacturer’ column. This was done by use string manipulation to grab only the car’s manufacturer rather than the unique model.

Should encoding be done in highest average price for categorical variables or should there just be OneHotEncoding?

  • Yes! This was proven at the end of the model analysis. There were higher values in the leading model, Random Forest Regression. This was giving more important features higher mapped values.

Does hyper tuning increase model performance dramatically?

  • Hyper tuning increase model performance for the Decision Tree Regression models. This was using only .01 or .02 in the R-squared.

The problem formulation:¶

What is it that we are trying to solve using data science?

  • The goal is to solve what a used car’s price value is using data science. With data science there are many statistical methods and tools to gather further insight into data. Using these tools, we can create visualizations that give us a better representation of what features impact used car value the most. While also giving answers about car brands and other features that have a large impact on used car popularity.

Data Dictionary¶

S.No. : Serial Number

Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name

Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (Cities)

Year : Manufacturing year of the car

Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM

Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)

Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic / Manual)

Owner : Type of ownership

Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg

Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC

Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp

Seats : The number of seats in the car

New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR 100,000

Price : The price of the used car in INR 100,000 (Target Variable)

Observations & Insights:

  • The first task was to drop the ‘S.No.’ column because there was no useful information besides index values for the date fame.

  • The second task was to notice any trends or information that can be extracted from the features. It was found that log transformations needed to be done to ‘Kilometers_Drive’, ‘Price’, and ‘New_Price’. This was done because of the large skewness to the right. Also, these columns had values that had very large ranges. By performing log transformations on these columns, we were able to show a somewhat normal distribution for these features.

  • The third task was to identify any bivariate relationships between variables using a correlation heatmap. It was found that ‘Power’ had the highest correlation to our target variable at .90.

  • The fourth task was to add some feature engineering into the dataset. The only feature that was added was the ‘Manufacturer’ column. This was created to take only the car’s Manufacturer instead of the unique model.

  • The fifth was missing and NULL value treatment. 87% of ‘New_price’ data was NULL so that column was dropped. Also, there were 17% of rows without pricing information. Since price was the target variable, those NULL rows were removed. Continuous feature’s missing values were filled with the median because that was shown as the best option when looking to the univariate analysis. The only feature that was treated specially was ‘Seat’ this was a continuous variable but was filled with the mean values for missing values. This was done to give more precise values to the feature. This was shown in the univariate analysis, and shows that the best filling value would be the mean rather than the median, because the median value gave a whole number rather than a float. Lastly, categorical variables were encoded with different methods.

  • The sixth step was the encoding process. I did two main processes for this. The first was to just normally encode the categorical features with pd.dummies. While this did give good insight into predictions, it was not the best performing model. The second encoding process was the best performing model. This encoding process was done by giving higher values to column values in each categorical feature by each column value’s average price. This was there was more importance given to models that had higher prices.

Building Various Models¶

Overview:

  • I would like to mention that I created 14 different machine learning models in total. But I separated the sections into model 1 and model 2. The reason for this is because I am still using the same machine learning models, but I had a different encoding process for both. Which contributed to the largest difference between the two different models. Both models had the target variable as ‘log_Price’, it was proven in the univariate analysis that this had a more normal distribution. So, this was chosen as the more accurate and better represented target variable. Both models have 7 sub-models that were created. Those models being Random Forest Regression, Decision Tree Regression, Linear Regression, Ridge Regression, and Lasso Regression. These were all taken from the scikit-learn packages.

Technique Comparison¶

  • Model 1: The encoding process for this model was simple. I used pd.dummies to encode all the categorical features. This way was simple, fast and easy. It was found that this model had success with over .90 R-squared value in the final predictions.

  • Model 2: This encoding process was done by mapping the value for each categorical variable to the average price during the bivariate analysis. By doing this I was able to give categorical features more importance, by mapping higher values to higher price averages. By combining this encoding process and the best performing machine learning model there was a consistent .936 R-squared score for this model.

  • Cross-Validation: Cross-validation was applied to every model. This was done to see any overfitting that was occurring in the models. When comparing these models to the test predictions it was found that no models were overfitting. This was fantastic. Cross-validation was applied using 10 K-folds.

  • Hyper-tuning: I applied hyper tuning using grid search to Random Forest Regression, Decision Tree Regression, and Ridge Regression. I only applied hyper tuning the Ridge Regression in the first model due to no changes in R-squared when doing final analysis. It was found that the Decision Tree Regression model performed better than the default model after being hyper turned. The Random Forest Regression model did not improve after hyper tuning.

  • Feature Importance: After hyper tuning, there was feature importance. I performed feature importance on Random Forest Regression and Decision Tree Regression. In model 2, they were the best performing models. Also, insight was needed into the function of each model. After comparing all models and features, it was found that the features with the most importance were ‘Power’ and ‘Year’. These were the most important features in both models. But in model 2 the third most important feature was ‘Manufacturer’ and in model 1 the third most important feature was ‘Engine’.

Proposal for Final Solution¶

Overview:

  • The final solution should be Model 2: Random Forest Regression. This was proven to have the best performance through cross-validation and through testing predictions. The final scores were compared using the R-squared values since this is a regression problem. This final model has cross-validation and a testing prediction of .936. This showed that there was no overfitting within the model and no underfitting as well.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize = (12, 7), kde = False, bins = None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    title = 'Univariate Analysis of ' + feature

    upper_outlier = data[feature].mean() + data[feature].std()*3
    lower_outlier = data[feature].mean() - data[feature].std()*3

    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows = 2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex = True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize = figsize,
    )  # Creating the 2 subplots
    plt.suptitle(title) # Add title to figure
    sns.boxplot(
        data = data, x = feature, ax = ax_box2, showmeans = True, color = "violet"
    )  # Boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data = data, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2, bins = bins, palette = "winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data = data, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2
    ) # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color = "green", linestyle = "--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color = "black", linestyle = "-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        upper_outlier, color = "red", linestyle = "-"
    )  # Add lower outlier line to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        lower_outlier, color = "red", linestyle = "-"
    )  # Add upper outlier line to the histogram

# Plot each feature for univariate analysis
for col in continuous_vars:
    histogram_boxplot(df, col)
    plt.savefig(col)

  • Power - Power has a slight skew to the right, but does offer somewhat of a normal distribution. The majority of power is just 80-110. There does seem to be some extreme outliers that are in power.

# Create lists of columns that need log transformations
log_columns= ['Kilometers_Driven','New_price','Price']
log_column_names= []

# Create loop to add the log transformations for each column in log_columns
for col in log_columns:
    logged_column_name = 'log_'+ col                # Create a new column for log transformations
    df[logged_column_name] = np.log(df[col])        # Perform the log transformation on column and put it into the dataframe
    log_column_names.append(logged_column_name)     # Add log_ + column_name to the empty list

Building Various Models¶

  1. What we want to predict is the "Price". We will use the normalized version 'price_log' for modeling.
  2. Before we proceed to the model, we'll have to encode categorical features. We will drop categorical features like Name.
  3. We'll split the data into train and test, to be able to evaluate the model that we build on the train data.
  4. Build Regression models using train data.
  5. Evaluate the model performance.

Split the Data¶

  • Step1: Seperating the indepdent variables (X) and the dependent variable (y).
  • Step2: Encode the categorical variables in X using pd.dummies.
  • Step3: Split the data into train and test using train_test_split.

    • Question:

    1. Why we should drop 'Name','Price','price_log','Kilometers_Driven' from X before splitting?

    Answer:

    • This would be done so that we do not have any information that is not needed in our predictions. Also we have better features that include log transformations.

# Create function for regression model analysis
def basic_regression(model_list, name_list, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):  

  # Create lists for training results
  trained_rs      = [] * len(model_list)
  trained_mae     = [] * len(model_list)
  trained_rmse    = [] * len(model_list)
  trained_time    = [] * len(model_list)
  trained_results = pd.DataFrame()

  # Loop through all Regressors and find best performing alogrithm
  for i in range(0,len(model_list)):

    # Assign and Start time
    start_time = time.time()         # Start time for model trainin & prediction
    trained_model = model_list[i]  # Assign Model to regression function   
      
    # Train and Predict model
    trained_model.fit(X_train, y_train)     # Fit the model on Training Data
    y_pred = trained_model.predict(X_test)  # Predict Values for X_test set
      
    # Calcualte & Insert Train time
    end_time = time.time()               # End Time
    total_time = end_time - start_time   # Calculate total time taken
    trained_time.insert(i,round(total_time, 1))    # Insert data into list

    # Insert Training Metrics into lists
    trained_rmse.insert(i, mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, squared=False))
    trained_mae.insert(i,mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))
    trained_rs.insert(i, r2_score(y_test, y_pred))

  # Add data into dataframe columns
  trained_results['Model'] = np.array(name_list)
  trained_results['Time_Taken'] = np.array(trained_time)
  trained_results['R-Squared'] = np.array(trained_rs)
  trained_results['Mean Absolute Error'] = np.array(trained_mae)
  trained_results['Root Mean Squared Error'] = np.array(trained_rmse)

  # Order Training Results
  trained_results = trained_results.sort_values(by='R-Squared', ascending=False)

  # Print Results of algorithm  
  print(' '*32,'REGRESSION FINAL REPORT')
  print('-'*93)
  print('Training Set Size:', len(X_train))
  print('Testing Set Size:', len(X_test))
  display(trained_results)

    def cross_val_regression(model_list, name_list, X_train, y_train, folds):
  '''
  Description: This will cross-validate a list of regression models.
  model_list: List of regression models.
  name_list: List of regression models names. 
  X_train: X_train dataset.
  y_train: y_train dataset.
  folds: # of K-folds for cross-validation.
  '''

  # Create lists for variables
  cross_results = pd.DataFrame()
  cross_r2      = [] * len(model_list)
  cross_mae     = [] * len(model_list)
  cross_mse     = [] * len(model_list)
  cross_time    = [] * len(model_list)
  
  for i in range(0, len(model_list)):
    
    # Assign and Start time
    start_time = time.time()         # Start time for model trainin & prediction
    
    model = model_list[i]
    r2    = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, n_jobs=-1)                 
    mae   = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, scoring = 'neg_mean_squared_error', n_jobs=-1)
    mse   = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error', n_jobs=-1)
    
    # Calcualte & Insert Train time
    end_time = time.time()               # End Time
    total_time = end_time - start_time   # Calculate total time taken

    # Insert info into lists
    cross_time.insert(i,round(total_time, 1))    # Insert data into list
    cross_r2.insert(i, round(r2.mean(), 3))
    cross_mae.insert(i, round(mae.mean()*-1, 3))
    cross_mse.insert(i, round(mse.mean()*-1, 3))

  # Create columns for dataFrame & input data
  cross_results['Model'] = np.array(name_list)
  cross_results['Time_Taken'] = np.array(cross_time)
  cross_results['R-Squared'] = np.array(cross_r2)
  cross_results['Mean Squared Error'] = np.array(cross_mse)
  cross_results['Mean Absolute Error'] = np.array(cross_mae)

  # Order Training Results
  cross_results = cross_results.sort_values(by='R-Squared', ascending=False)

  print(' '*32,'CROSS VALIDATION REPORT')
  print('-'*89)
  display(cross_results)

# Run Cross Validation

# Create function for evaluating hypertuned machine learning models & their original algorithms
def evaluate_hypertuned_model(model,model_name, hypertuned_model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, folds):
    '''
    Description: This will output a cross validation & training/testing scores for hypertuned models and default regression models.
    model: The default regression model.
    model_name: The name of the regression model.
    hypertuned_model: The hypertuned regression model.
    X_train: X_train dataset.
    y_train: y_train dataset.
    X_test: X_test dataset.
    y_test: y_test dataset.
    folds: # of K-folds for cross validation.
    '''

    # Define metric arrays
    orig_results  = pd.DataFrame()
    cross_results = pd.DataFrame()

    cross_name = [] * 2
    orig_name  = [] * 2

    cross_r2  = [] * 2
    cross_mae = [] * 2
    cross_mse = [] * 2

    orig_r2  = [] * 2
    orig_mae = [] * 2
    orig_mse = [] * 2
    
    # Evaluate Original Cross Validation on Model
    basic_cross_r2    = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, n_jobs=-1)                 
    basic_cross_mae   = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, scoring = 'neg_mean_squared_error', n_jobs=-1)
    basic_cross_mse   = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error', n_jobs=-1)  

    # Insert Original Model metrics into lists
    cross_name.insert(0, 'Default ' + model_name)
    cross_r2.insert(0, round(basic_cross_r2.mean(), 3))
    cross_mae.insert(0, round(basic_cross_mae.mean()*-1, 3))
    cross_mse.insert(0, round(basic_cross_mse.mean()*-1, 3))

    # Evaluate Cross Validation on Hypertuned Model
    hyper_cross_r2    = cross_val_score(hypertuned_model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, n_jobs=-1)                 
    hyper_cross_mae   = cross_val_score(hypertuned_model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, scoring = 'neg_mean_squared_error', n_jobs=-1)
    hyper_cross_mse   = cross_val_score(hypertuned_model, X_train, y_train, cv = folds, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error', n_jobs=-1) 
    
    # Insert Hypertuned metrics into lists
    cross_name.insert(1, ('Hypertuned '+ model_name))
    cross_r2.insert(1, round(hyper_cross_r2.mean(), 3))
    cross_mae.insert(1, round(hyper_cross_mae.mean()*-1, 3))
    cross_mse.insert(1, round(hyper_cross_mse.mean()*-1, 3))

    # Add data into dataframe columns
    cross_results['Model'] = pd.Series(cross_name)
    cross_results['R-Squared'] = pd.Series(cross_r2)
    cross_results['Mean Absolute Error'] = pd.Series(cross_mae)
    cross_results['Mean Squared Error'] = pd.Series(cross_mse)

    # Sort Results
    cross_results = cross_results.sort_values(by='R-Squared', ascending=False)

    # Print Out results
    print('\n\n', ' '*32,'CROSS VALIDATION REPORT')
    print('-'*89)
    display(cross_results)

    #Testing & Training

    # Original Model Training and Testing
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    orig_y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Insert Training Metrics into lists
    orig_name.insert(0, 'Default ' + model_name)
    orig_r2.insert(0, round(r2_score(y_test, orig_y_pred), 3))
    orig_mae.insert(0, round(mean_absolute_error(y_test, orig_y_pred), 3))
    orig_mse.insert(0, round(mean_squared_error(y_test, orig_y_pred, squared=False), 3))
    
    # Hypertuned Training and Testing
    hypertuned_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    hypertuned_y_pred = hypertuned_model.predict(X_test)

    # Insert Training Metrics into lists
    orig_name.insert(1, 'Hypertuned '+ model_name)
    orig_r2.insert(1, round(r2_score(y_test, hypertuned_y_pred), 3))
    orig_mae.insert(1, round(mean_absolute_error(y_test, hypertuned_y_pred), 3))
    orig_mse.insert(1, round(mean_squared_error(y_test, hypertuned_y_pred, squared=False), 3))

    # Add data into dataframe columns
    orig_results['Model'] = pd.Series(orig_name)
    orig_results['R-Squared'] = pd.Series(orig_r2)
    orig_results['Mean Absolute Error'] = pd.Series(orig_mae)
    orig_results['Mean Squared Error'] = pd.Series(orig_mse)

    # Sort Results
    orig_results = orig_results.sort_values(by='R-Squared', ascending=False)

    # Print Results of algorithm  
    print('\n\n',' '*32,'REGRESSION FINAL REPORT')
    print('-'*93)
    print('Training Set Size:', len(X_train))
    print('Testing Set Size:', len(X_test))
    display(orig_results)

    # Create Tree Regression Importance Function for further use
def tree_regression_importance(model, X_train, y_train, top_values, model_name):
    '''
    Description: This will output features of importance in a tree regression model.
    X_train: X_train dataset.
    y_train: y_train dataset.
    top_values: The top # of features of importance.
    model_name: The name of the tree regression model.
    '''

    # Create title for Chart
    title = 'Top ' + str(top_values) + ' features for '+ model_name
    # Fit model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Create list to hold features values
    feature_list = []

    # Extract feature names and their importance
    for feature, importance in zip(X_train.columns, model.feature_importances_):  
        temp = [feature, importance]
        feature_list.append(temp)

    # Create Pandas DataFrame
    importance_df= pd.DataFrame(feature_list, columns = ['Feature', 'Importance'])
    importance_df= importance_df.sort_values('Importance', ascending = False)
    display(importance_df)

    # Create Barchart
    sns.barplot(data=importance_df[0:top_values],
                x='Importance',
                y='Feature',
                orient='h')

    # Title for chart
    plt.title(title)

    Conclusions and Recommendations¶

    1. Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance based on chosen Metric (Measure of success):

    • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?
    • Answer: The main difference between the two models are the encoding methods.
    • Model 1: used pd.dummies to encode the dataframe. This was so that all categorical variables were give same values of importance from the start.
    • Model 2: The encoding method for model 2 was to encode the the categorical variables by there average price. This way there could be more importance given to the categorical variables that had a higher average price.

    2. Refined insights:

    • What are the most meaningful insights relevant to the problem?
    • Answer: That the log transformation can give huge insights to normal distribution patterns in independent variables.
    • Power is the most important feature in the 2 highest performing models. This was infered earlier when looking at the heatmap correlations between Power and log_Price.

    3. Proposal for the final solution design:

    • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?
    • Model 2 Random Forest Regression: The reason for this is that the Random Forest Regression model has the higher performance based on R-squared score from any other model. After running both models through cross validation model2's Random Forest Regression's R-squared score remained the same. Judging by this information, I found that model 2 Random forest regression was the best perfoming model and should be adopted as the final solution with an R-squared score of .936!

    Exectutive Summary¶

    The important findings for this are that Power, Year and Manufacturer are the 3 largest predictors when it comes to used car predictions. The next steps would be to see how we can input current market conditions that include supply and demand. This would give a higher accuracy to our predictions in this model. The final model is stated above and shows that the model 2 and encoding process will be the best way to predict used car prices.

    The only challenges would be to see how these predictions were correlated with new car price. The only costs that would be associated with this model would be the server to run the model on and the web scraping software needed to pull on information for this prediction model.
